  `src/tests.rs`:
    - test_pass_new        : 11 cases   -> pn01..pn11 here
    - test_include_section :  5 cases   -> inc1..inc5 here
    - test_pass_old        :  1 case    == example.lp (the repo's only `.lp` file)
  We harvested the 17 case INPUTS (the `source` argument / first string of each pair),
  NEVER the `result`/expected-output (golden) strings. pn01..pn11 and inc1..inc5 are
  transcribed from those inline input literals (escapes decoded, raw strings verbatim);
  example.lp is byte-identical to the test_pass_old input.

  COMMITTED: 17 of 17 inputs (pn01..pn11, inc1..inc5, example.lp) — each verified
  idempotent AND `≈`-safe AND parseable under the vendored grammar at
  width 100.

  example.lp / the test_pass_old input is the deliberately-adversarial comment-torture
  rule (the `bla ... #sum { ... }` rule, with `%aa`/`%bb` comments scattered between
  EVERY token mid-aggregate). It surfaced a whole CLASS of comment-transposition `≈`-bug:
  a pending own-line comment that preceded a FOLLOWING token carrying a trailing comment
  was emitted AFTER that trailing comment (the pair reordered). The fix closed the `,`/`;`
  SEPARATOR facet first, then the rest of the class — the comment now leads ANY
  following token (the `:-`/`:~`/`:` necks, the `{`/`(`/`[` openers, the `=`/`@` infixes;
  the dual-purpose `|` is the sole carve-out). That single classifier change also
  resolved the coupled non-idempotence (a nested aggregate element's comment had drifted
  indent across reformat, driven by the mis-attached neck comments above it).
  example.lp is now fully `≈`-safe and idempotent at width 100, so it is admitted.
